Line 62 of /Users/lmoura/projects/martis/martis-package/src/Sso/Providers/AzureProvider.php reads:

    $accessToken = method_exists($user, 'token') ? null : null;

Both branches of the ternary return `null`, so the `method_exists` check is pure dead code — the result is always `null` regardless of whether a `token` method exists.

Lines 63-66 then recover the token only via `property_exists`:

    if (property_exists($user, 'token')) {
        $accessToken = (string) $user->token;
    }

So `$accessToken` is `null` whenever `token` is exposed by the Socialite driver as a method or getter (e.g. `getToken()`) rather than as a direct public property. If that is the case, `$accessToken` remains `null`.

Line 68 coerces it:

    $externalRoles = $this->fetchExternalRoles($externalId, $accessToken ?? '');

`null ?? ''` produces `''`. Line 88 then gates on the empty string:

    if ($accessToken === '') {
        return [];
    }

So when the Socialite driver exposes `token` only as a method (not a public property), `fetchExternalRoles` returns an empty array and all role fetching is silently skipped. No exception is thrown; the user is still authenticated, just with no external roles mapped.

The claim in the report is accurate. The `method_exists` ternary is genuine dead code (both arms return `null`), and the recovery path only handles the public-property case. Drivers that expose the token via a method call will silently lose all role assignments.

The severity is correctly "high" for SSO contexts where role-based access control is the gate on what the authenticated user is allowed to do. Silent role omission means a user could authenticate successfully but land with no permissions, or (depending on how the Martis role mapper works with an empty external-roles list) potentially with a default role that grants more access than intended. The reporter's suggested fix is sound: prefer `$user->token` (works for both public property and magic __get), then fall back to a known getter if needed, and remove the dead ternary.

